#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:5
msgid "Function Pointer Issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:7
msgid "There are two main issues with function pointers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:11
msgid "Function pointer casts can cause function pointer calls to fail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:13
msgid ""
"Function pointers must be called with the correct type: it is undefined "
"behavior in C/C++ to cast a function pointer to another type and call it "
"that way. This does work in most native platforms, however, despite it being "
"UB, but in Wasm it can fail. In that case, you may see an error like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:19
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:25
msgid "or ``abort(10)`` or some other number (depending on the type of build)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:27
msgid "Rarely, you may see a compiler warning like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:33
msgid ""
"This may be related to a function pointer cast problem as implicit "
"declarations may have a different type than how you call them. However, in "
"general the compiler cannot warn about this, and you will only see a problem "
"at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:36
msgid ""
"Older versions of :term:`clang` can generate different code for C and C++ "
"calls when a structure is passed **by value** (for completeness, one "
"convention is ``struct byval`` and the other is ``field a, field b``). The "
"two formats are incompatible with each other, and you may get a warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:38
msgid ""
"The workaround is to pass the structure by reference, or simply not mix C "
"and C++ in that location (for example, rename the **.c** file to **.cpp**)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:45
msgid "Debugging function pointer issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:47
msgid ""
"The ``SAFE_HEAP`` and ``ASSERTION`` options can catch some of these errors "
"at runtime and provide useful information. You can also see if "
"``EMULATE_FUNCTION_POINTER_CASTS`` fixes things for you, but see later down "
"about the overhead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:49
msgid "You can get compiler errors for some of these problems with"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:56
msgid "Working around function pointer issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:58
msgid "There are three solutions to this problem (the second is preferred):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:60
msgid ""
"Cast the function pointer back to the correct type before it is called. This "
"is problematic because it requires that the caller knows the original type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:61
msgid ""
"Manually write an adapter function that does not need to be cast, and calls "
"the original function. For example, it might ignore a parameter, and in that "
"way bridge between the different function pointer types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/function_pointer_issues.rst:62
msgid ""
"Use ``EMULATE_FUNCTION_POINTER_CASTS``. When you build with ``-"
"sEMULATE_FUNCTION_POINTER_CASTS``, Emscripten emits code to emulate function "
"pointer casts at runtime, adding extra arguments/dropping them/changing "
"their type/adding or dropping a return type/etc. This can add significant "
"runtime overhead, so it is not recommended, but is worth trying."
msgstr ""

